Done
what was the problem with async_wait?

It didn't work in my testing, because a test stream doesn't have async wait.  Doing async_read_some allowed me to not have to wrap

https://www.boost.org/doc/libs/develop/libs/beast/doc/html/beast/ref/boost__beast__test__stream.html

In a separate class to try to simulate all the behaviors of a socket.
wait is more general, will catch all error including writes. If you are worried only about connection termination , then read will do the job I guess. I am ok with this.
How do we arrive this 10MB buffer limit?
it’s arbitrary, but higher than we should ever see in practice.

yes, right, thinking why 10MB is needed in this case?
keep it to 1MB ?
in theory a couple large messages could fill a 1MB buffer.  10mb seemed safer, especially given that there aren’t currently limits.

looks like multi_buffer memory will be held till the life time of connection object. So if the multi_buffer allowed to grow to 10MB will not it be considered as memory leak?. Or are you saying that if there is no more data to be sent, the connection will be closed and object will be destroyed? 

Do you want to consider using shrink_to_fit after consume?

calling shrink_to_fit seems like a good idea.  I don't think that would be part of this commit, as it's not changing anything to do with the buffer. Abhilash, do you want to submit that as its own patch?
I am ok with that
case missing for the closehandler true. When are we expecting the sse connection to close? Is it a long-lasting push stream?
what does closehandler true mean?  we don't test that closing works?

nevermind, I figured it out.  Code added to check the close handler.

Yes, SSE is a long lived connection.
Acknowledged
this is a bit more than unit tests, it some refactoring.. It would be good to state that.
Done
